---
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import Math from '../components/Math.astro';
---

<Section id="speed-arches" number="3" title="Speed, arches, and exit jams">
  <p>
    When a crowd rushes, agents pressing from slightly different angles
    convert their forward push into <em>lateral</em> normal force through
    wedge geometry. Friction then prevents any keystone from sliding. Once
    three agents form this configuration the arch locks, and every agent
    pressing from behind tightens it further. The crowd is not stopped by
    a wall; it is stopped by itself.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <img src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/figures/evac_time_plot.png`.replace(/\/+/g, '/')} alt="Mean evacuation time vs desired speed, with 95% confidence intervals" />
    <figcaption>
      <strong>Figure 1.</strong> Mean evacuation time
      <Math tex={String.raw`\pm`} /> 95 % CI vs. desired speed <Math tex={String.raw`v_0`} />
      (<Math tex={String.raw`N = 60`} />, 1 m exit, 5 seeds). The optimal
      band sits between orderly queueing and arch-dominated jamming; the
      large confidence interval at high <Math tex={String.raw`v_0`} />
      reflects stochastic arch-escape timing.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Figure&nbsp;1 reveals the full picture: a U-shaped evacuation curve.
    Below <Math tex={String.raw`v_0 \approx 2.2\,\text{m/s}`} /> agents
    queue in orderly single file, slow but smooth. Above
    <Math tex={String.raw`v_0 \approx 3.0\,\text{m/s}`} /> arch formation
    becomes self-sustaining and evacuation time rises sharply. We call
    this the <strong>faster-is-slower (FIS) effect</strong>: wanting to go
    faster makes you leave slower.
  </p>

  <p>
    The mechanism is worth stating precisely because the rest of the
    paper depends on it. Two agents arriving at the doorway from
    slightly different angles convert part of their forward push into a
    lateral force along their contact line. If the sliding friction
    <Math tex={String.raw`\kappa`} /> is large enough to balance that
    lateral force, neither agent slides past the other. A third agent
    pressing from behind closes the configuration into a small
    self-supporting arch. The wall is not holding the crowd back; the
    crowd is holding itself. The optimal
    <Math tex={String.raw`v_0`} /> in Figure&nbsp;1 is the value at
    which the marginal benefit of moving faster (shorter time per
    crossing) and the marginal cost (higher probability of an arch)
    balance.
  </p>

  <p>
    The faster-is-slower effect is therefore purely mechanical: it does
    not require panic, contagion, or any model of the crowd's emotional
    state. But it does require something to raise
    <Math tex={String.raw`v_0`} /> in the first place, and that
    something, in a real evacuation, is panic. The next section
    introduces a model for how panic spreads, and the one after that
    closes the loop by linking the spread back to
    <Math tex={String.raw`v_0`} />.
  </p>
</Section>
